english:
  title: Edict of Condolence to the Sons of Kim Bu-ui, Director of the Secretariat, Upon His Passing
  author: Choe Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To Jongjdo and others, I decree:

    Your father, Kim Bu-ui—holder of the Purple Insignia, Grand Master of Remonstrance, Guardian of the Ministry of Personnel, Left Vice Minister of the Secretariat, Academician of the Hall of Government, Judge of Rites in the Board of Ceremonies, Compiler of the National History, and Pillar of State—possessed talents so extraordinary and wondrous that they captivated all who beheld and heard of him. His learning was so lofty and expansive that it touched the very wellsprings of the Way itself.

    In his writings flowed the boundless spirit of one who rides the clouds; in his deeds manifested the steadfast counsel of one who strengthens the realm. With his unfettered spirit and noble bearing, he was bound by no petty conventions. Since my years in retirement before the throne, I knew well his virtue and wisdom. Thus did I gradually elevate him to the highest ranks, until he reached the office of Director of the Secretariat. There I consulted with him in the inner chambers, hoping through his counsel to extend peace and prosperity throughout the realm.

    Yet suddenly word came of his passing, and my heart is truly grieved. Once I believed that the virtuous must surely live long; how then has this wise man withered away? Not only do travelers in the streets lament, but the entire court mourns. And yet the principle of life and death is the same for sage and saint alike. I urge you therefore: devote yourselves fully to filial piety and conduct the funeral rites with propriety, but do not grieve to excess and thereby harm yourselves.

    I send the Assistant Commissioner of the Palace Workshops, Shin Gong-yeong, to offer condolences and bring you comfort.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Bu-ui held numerous prestigious positions in the Goryeo administration, indicating his high rank and influence at court.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "years in retirement before the throne" (잠저) refers to the period before the author's ascension to power, when he knew Kim Bu-ui personally.
  - key: ''
    value: This edict exemplifies the formal consolatory genre common in classical East Asian statecraft, balancing personal grief with philosophical resignation to the natural order.
